items.abstract: <jats:p>A massive MIMO wireless system is a multiuser MISO system where base stations consist of a large number of antennas with respect to number of user devices, each equipped with a single antenna. Massive MIMO is seen as the way forward in enhancing the transmission rate and user capacity in 5G wireless. The potential of massive MIMO system lies in the ability to almost always realize multiuser channels with near zero mutual coupling. Coupling factor reduces by 1/2 for each doubling of transmit antennas. In a high bit rate massive MIMO system with <mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="M1"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math> base station antennas and <mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="M2"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>n</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math> users, downlink capacity increases as <mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="M3"><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">log</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn fontstyle="italic">2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow><mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi>m</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math> bps/Hz, and the capacity per user reduces as <mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="M4"><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:msub><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">log</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mn fontstyle="italic">2</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:msub></mml:mrow><mml:mo>⁡</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi>n</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math> bps/Hz. This capacity can be achieved by power sharing and using signal weighting vectors aligned to respective <mml:math xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="M5"><mml:mn mathvariant="normal">1</mml:mn><mml:mo>×</mml:mo><mml:mi>m</mml:mi></mml:math> channels of the users. For low bit rate transmission, time sharing achieves the capacity as much as power sharing does. System capacity reduces as channel coupling factor increases. Interference avoidance or minimization strategies can be used to achieve the available capacity in such scenarios. Probability distribution of channel coupling factor is a convenient tool to predict the number of antennas needed to qualify a system as massive MIMO.</jats:p>
title: On the Capacity and Transmission Techniques of Massive MIMO Systems
